# TubeWatch Project Architecture Rules

## Purpose

This rule file defines the required project architecture for TubeWatch.

All generated code must follow the documented project structure and preserve block-based modularity.

Do not restructure the project unless explicitly instructed.

---

## Architecture Model

TubeWatch uses a Block Development Architecture.

Main blocks:

- Block A — Feature Engine
- Block B — Gemini AI Engine
- Block C — YouTube Data Fetch
- Block D — Storage Layer
- Block E — Worker
- Block F — UI Layer

Each block has a clearly defined responsibility.

---

## Required Separation of Concerns

Keep each block isolated.

Do not mix the following responsibilities in the same module unless explicitly instructed:

- YouTube data fetching
- feature generation
- AI analysis
- database storage
- UI rendering

Examples:

- Feature Engine must not perform database writes
- AI Engine must not fetch YouTube data
- UI must not contain analysis logic
- Storage Layer must not generate AI insights

---

## Preferred Project Structure

Use the existing project structure unless instructed otherwise.

Preferred directories:

- src/app
- src/components
- src/features
- src/lib
- src/types
- docs
- .cursor/rules

Use feature-based grouping where appropriate.

---

## File Placement Rules

Place files according to responsibility.

Examples:

- feature logic → src/features/
- shared UI components → src/components/
- route handlers → src/app/api/
- app pages → src/app/
- shared utility logic → src/lib/
- shared types → src/types/ or block-local types files

Do not place unrelated logic in the wrong directory.

---

## Block Boundary Rules

When implementing a block:

- work only inside the requested block
- do not modify unrelated blocks
- do not anticipate future blocks unless explicitly requested
- keep interfaces between blocks clear and minimal

Each block should expose only the functions needed by downstream modules.

---

## Pipeline Architecture

All analysis-related code must follow this pipeline:

YouTube Fetch  
↓  
Feature Engine  
↓  
Gemini AI Analysis  
↓  
Storage Layer  
↓  
UI Layer

Do not bypass this pipeline without explicit instruction.

---

## Dependency Rules

Dependencies should follow the pipeline direction.

Allowed pattern:

- Fetch → Feature
- Feature → AI
- AI → Storage
- Storage → UI read path through backend/API

Avoid reverse coupling.

Examples of disallowed coupling:

- Feature Engine importing UI modules
- UI importing worker logic
- AI Engine directly depending on page components

---

## Modification Rules

Before modifying existing files:

- check whether the file belongs to the current block
- preserve existing architecture unless the task requires change
- avoid broad refactors during block implementation
- prefer minimal, targeted modifications

---

## Architecture Validation

Before completing a task, verify:

- files are placed in the correct folders
- block boundaries are preserved
- unrelated modules are untouched
- pipeline order is respected
- no responsibility leakage exists across layers

---

## Rule Summary

Always preserve:

- block isolation
- folder responsibility
- pipeline consistency
- modular structure
- predictable integration boundaries

